	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>PSP analog stick or perhaps the D-pad moves on its own!</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yesterday, I was out for a walk and slipped on a patch of ice. I had my PSP 2000 in my breast pocket. I landed on my thigh, not on my chest or anything. After I got up I checked my PSP and it seemed to be fine, until later when I tried to launch a game.
<br />
<br />The problem I'm experiencing is whenever I launch any PSP game or any homebrew, the analog stick is constantly pushing to the left.
<br />
<br />I read online about the problem and that its usually caused by dirty connections or loose screws.
<br />
<br />I did the obvious system information recalibration, but that didn't seem to work. I applied pressure to the faceplate, but again that didn't do a whole lot once I let go of the pressure on the faceplate.
<br />
<br />So, I've opened it up and removed the analog nub assembly completely. What am i suppose to do with it? It doesn't look especially dirty, but I'd like to clean it to see if that will help.
<br />
<br />Here's the part that has me worried. Just out of curiosity, I tried powering the PSP back on with the analog nub completely removed - and the right analog input is still being registered as constantly on! How can that even be with the nub completely removed? The only thing I can think of is perhaps its a problem with the D-pad, but in the main PSP menu the D-pad works correctly. I'm confused.
<br />
<br />Anyone have any suggestions for things I should try?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
